City of Fairfax Calls for Service Data

id.calls <- "1gRoL7lZlwm7sreA5F9WbPoH5su4n4iGS"
calls.temp <- read.csv(sprintf("https://docs.google.com/uc?id=%s&export=download", id.calls))

Wrangle Data

calls.temp$date <- as.Date(calls.temp$date)
calls.temp$dow <-weekdays(calls.temp$date)
calls.temp$day <- day(calls.temp$date)
calls.temp$month <- substr(calls.temp$date, 6, 7)

Calculate Data

# Step 3
calls.type <- calls.temp %>%
  group_by(type) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(PCT = round(count/sum(count)*100,2))
calls <- subset(calls.temp, calls.temp$type == 'ACCIDENT- NO INJURY')

calls.day <- calls %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarise(count = n())

# Day of week and hour of day
calls.day.time <- calls %>%
  group_by(dow, hour) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'dow'. You can override using the `.groups`
## argument.
calls.day.time <- subset(calls.day.time, !is.na(calls.day.time$hour))

# Month of year and year
calls.year.month <- calls %>%
  group_by(year, month) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
calls.year.month <- subset(calls.year.month, !is.na(calls.year.month$month))

#Day of week, Hour of day, & year
calls.year.day.time <- calls %>%
  group_by(year, dow, hour) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year', 'dow'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
calls.year.day.time <- subset(calls.year.day.time, !is.na(calls.year.day.time$hour))

# Day of month, month of year
calls.month.day <- calls %>%
  group_by(month, day) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'month'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
calls.month.day <- subset(calls.month.day, 
!is.na(calls.month.day$day))

                          
first <- min(calls.day$date)
last <- max(calls.day$date)

calls.day <- calls.day %>% 
  complete(date = seq(ymd(first), 
                      ymd(last), 
                      "day")) %>%
  mutate(dow = wday(date, label = T, week_start = 1), 
         month.name = month(date, label = T, abbr = F),
         month.num = substr(date, 6,7),
         week = isoweek(date),
         day = day(date),
         year = year(date))

calls.day$count[is.na(calls.day$count)] = "0"
calls.day$count <- as.numeric(calls.day$count)

high <- as.numeric(max(calls.day$count))
low <- as.numeric(min(calls.day$count))
mean <- mean(calls.day$count)
sd <- sd(calls.day$count)

calls.day <- mutate(calls.day, 
                    week = case_when(month.name == "December" & week == 1 ~ 53,
                                     month.name == "January" & week %in% 52:53 ~ 0,
                                     TRUE ~ week),
                    category = cut(count, c(low-1, (mean-sd*3), (mean-sd*2), (mean-sd), mean, (mean+sd), (mean+sd*2), 
                                            (mean+sd*3), high+1)))

Typologies with Analysis

Analysis

By looking at the above Typology, hotspots are scattered; during each month, there has been at least one hotspot based on the day ranging from 73 to almost 90 calls each day. For example, the highest amount was on November 9th; there were 88 accident-no-injury calls according to the Day of Month and Month of Year typology. However, when looking at the Month of Year and Year Typology, there is one in Oct 2009, two in Oct and Dec 2011, and one in May 2012, reaching almost 200 calls. As for coldspots, it has been more prominent from 2017 into the beginning of 2023, ranging from 30 to 120 calls each month; in the Day of Month Typology, there were only 18 calls on December 25th, while in the Month of Year Typology in February there would be only 11 calls made. According to the Month of Year Typology, there is a clear sign that these calls are decreasing based on many contributing factors, with the Covid Pandemic being one of those factors. I predict that in August 2023, there will be little to no activity for calls because there has not been any indication of activity from May and June or even reported in July.

Analysis

The Day of Week Histogram shows a constant decrease of accident no injury calls each day per week. The hotspots occur on Fridays, with the highest at 362 with two hotspots, one hotspot on Thursday at 315 accident no injury calls, and one on Wednesday at 359. Coldspots can take place throughout the week, depending on time. These accident-no-injury calls usually range from 2 to 100 each day; however, on Sundays, it seems to be the day with little to no activity, which can be shown on the Day of Week histogram above. I predict that next week, there will be a high level of accident-no-injury calls ranging from 150 to 200 accident-no-injury calls on Friday. Sunday accident-no-injury calls can vary from 10 to 100, depending on the time of day.

The above Typology shows that the hotspots usually occur between 3 to 5 pm. During that time frame, accident-no-injury calls can reach up to about 380 accident-no-injury calls. As for coldspots, it arises from 10 pm to 6 am. When these accident-no-injury calls receive little to no activity, those accident-no-injury calls can range between 2 to 80 accident-no-injury calls during that period. The trend of the hour of the day for this accident no injury calls will decrease then increase slightly; however, it would almost repeat each hour of each day. From the Typology, there is a clear pattern from 10 pm to 6 am. It will remain will little to no accident-no-injury calls while, when it is getting to 7 am – 9 pm, the accident-no-injury calls will gradually increase with accident-no-injury calls ranging from 100 to over 300 accident-no-injury calls each hour.
